            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Lee, at 31, embodies a quiet strength cultivated through a life shaped by a blend of tradition and personal exploration. Born in the Richmond District to immigrant parents from Hong Kong, his childhood was steeped in a mix of Cantonese spoken at home, Sunday dim sum gatherings, and the practical realities of his parents operating a small dry-cleaning business. While academically encouraged, David\u2019s early creative inclinations were often seen as secondary to more \u2018stable\u2019 pursuits. This initial subtle friction fueled a quiet internal resolve.\n\nHis path to Art Therapy wasn't linear. After initial pressure to pursue a more conventional STEM degree, David found himself adrift during his first year of college. A mandatory introductory \"Psychology of Art\" course proved a revelation, sparking a dormant passion for the therapeutic potential of creative expression. He switched majors, diving into the intersection of art, psychology, and social work at a local university. His practicum work in an underserved community center, witnessing firsthand the transformative power of art with children facing challenges, solidified his career path.\n\nSecuring his first job as an Art Therapist in a San Francisco public school district was a pivotal moment, a tangible validation of his chosen direction. Early years were marked by navigating bureaucratic hurdles and advocating for the value of art therapy within the educational system. A key turning point came when he successfully implemented a small group therapy program for students struggling with anxiety, observing significant positive shifts.\n\nDavid's personal life is a tapestry woven with close, intentional connections. He maintains a strong bond with his parents, often helping out at the dry cleaners on weekends, a silent nod to their sacrifices. His core social circle consists of fellow artists and therapists from his university days, meeting for gallery openings or weekend hikes in Marin Headlands. He\u2019s also actively involved in a community garden project in Golden Gate Park, finding solace and connection in cultivating the earth.\n\nHis current lifestyle is a reflection of his values \u2013 grounded and mindful. His daily routine involves an invigorating bike ride through the park to his job, time spent guiding students through creative expression, quiet evenings often spent sketching or reading, and an unwavering commitment to his own self-care through art.\n\nDavid's hopes and dreams are intertwined with his profession and the city he calls home. He aspires to expand the reach of art therapy in public schools, perhaps even establishing his own non-profit focusing on art and mental wellness for young people. He dreams of a day when art therapy is recognized as an essential component of comprehensive healthcare. His connection to San Francisco is deep-seated; it\u2019s the city that challenged him, nurtured his passion, and provided the backdrop for his evolving journey. He finds beauty in its contradictions, resilience in its people, and endless inspiration in its vibrant creative pulse."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  The smell of warm dough and shouting in Cantonese. Sunday mornings at the dim sum restaurant weren't just breakfast; they were sensory overload and feeling utterly safe. Watching his parents order for everyone, the easy rhythm of their language \u2013 it instilled a deep, quiet understanding of belonging and family, a constant anchor in a world that often felt uncertain. This was constant throughout his childhood.\n\n2.  Sitting in the psychology lecture hall, half-tuned out, when the professor showed slides of art created in therapy. Something clicked. It wasn't just pretty pictures; it was raw emotion, stories told without words. A sudden jolt of recognition, like finding a missing piece of himself. This was during his first year of college, a turning point toward his purpose.\n\n3.  Holding a child's hesitant hand as they painted a swirling storm of purple and black. Seeing the tension leave their shoulders, the quiet relief when they could finally express what words couldn't grasp. This moment, early in his practicum, solidified his belief in art's power and affirmed his path; it was the undeniable proof he needed.\n\n4.  The sheer exhaustion and elation after submitting his final thesis for his Art Therapy degree. Months of late nights, self-doubt, and intense work culminating in a tangible accomplishment. A deep sense of earned pride and validation, knowing he had followed his unconventional path and succeeded on his own terms. This marked the end of his formal training.\n\n5.  Standing in his small school therapy room, sunlight streaming through the window, looking at the colorful, messy creations on the walls. Each piece a silent testament to vulnerability and healing. A profound feeling of fulfillment, knowing this was where he belonged, doing work that mattered, right here in the city that felt like home. This was in his early years as an Art Therapist."
